03563nam a22005175i 9780822371632DE-B159720200928045905.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200928t20182018ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223716327 a10.1515/97808223716322doi  a(DE-B1597)554009  a(OCoLC)1013489851  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aART0490002bisacsh  aLO 75035qBSZ2rvk1 aTlostanova, Madina, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhat Does It Mean to Be Post-Soviet? :bDecolonial Art from the Ruins of the Soviet Empire /cMadina Tlostanova. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (160 p.) :b21 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aOn Decoloniality00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tINTRODUCTION. A Futureless Ontology? -- tCHAPTER ONE. The Decolonial Sublime -- tCHAPTER TWO. Decolonial Aesthesis and Post-Soviet Art -- tCHAPTER THREE. A Woman Who Has Many Selves and Takes Over Many Spaces: A Conversation with Liina Siib -- tCHAPTER FOUR. Beyond Dependencies: A Talk with Vyacheslav Akhunov, the Lonely Ranger of Uzbek Contemporary Art -- tCHAPTER FIVE. Reflecting on Time, Space, and Memory with Afanassy Mamedov -- tCONCLUSION. People Are Silent . . -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn What Does It Mean to Be Post-Soviet? Madina Tlostanova traces how contemporary post-Soviet art mediates this human condition. Observing how the concept of the happy future-which was at the core of the project of Soviet modernity-has lapsed from the post-Soviet imagination, Tlostanova shows how the possible way out of such a sense of futurelessness lies in the engagement with activist art. She interviews artists, art collectives, and writers such as Estonian artist Liina Siib, Uzbek artist Vyacheslav Akhunov, and Azerbaijani writer Afanassy Mamedov who frame the post-Soviet condition through the experience and expression of community, space, temporality, gender, and negotiating the demands of the state and the market. In foregrounding the unfolding aesthesis and activism in the post-Soviet space, Tlostanova emphasizes the important role that decolonial art plays in providing the foundation upon which to build new modes of thought and a decolonial future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 7aART / Russian & Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2018z978311069633240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822371632zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822371632423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822371632.jpg  a978-3-11-069633-2  DUK eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles